Recent advances in Generative AI (GenAI) tools—such as ChatGPT, Gemini, and GitHub Copilot, are reshaping computer science education. These technologies raise concerns around academic integrity and assessment but also offer significant opportunities to deepen understanding, enhance problem-solving, and expand access to learning support. This panel features faculty from three diverse CAE-CD, designated institutions -- a large urban community college, a small rural community college, and a baccalaureate-granting university, who will share practical approaches to integrating GenAI across the undergraduate curriculum, from CS0 and CS1 to cybersecurity courses and capstone experiences. Drawing on classroom examples, student feedback, and early assessment data, panelists will discuss strategies for supporting core computing competencies while promoting responsible use of GenAI. Topics include prompt-engineering/crafting scaffolds, AI-assisted coding and debugging, GenAI-infused assignments, and methods for evaluating student work in AI-rich environments. The session concludes with an open discussion, offering attendees actionable practices and insights for effectively and responsibly incorporating GenAI in their own courses.